  "texts": [
    "We observe a bias in the error rates towards dephasing, generally larger than 100:1 up to at least T = 1.5 K, for which increased fault-tolerant thresholds are possible [54] [55] [56].",
    "To exploit such gains, further research would be needed to characterize the process of error syndrome extraction, in which each cycle involves SPAM on the ancilla qubits during which the data qubits can undergo decoupling.",
    "We expect a moderate decrease in the noise bias from decoupling with increasing temperatures (Extended Data Fig. 5a), but this may not be true for even higher temperatures.",
    "The CZ-type operation we use as a 2-qubit gate can be bias-preserving, but fully exploiting this bias for QEC will require syndrome extraction circuit design to avoid injection of spin-flip errors from SPAM of the ancilla qubits into the data qubits.",
    "The use of algorithmic qubit initialization and the realization of high-fidelity universal logic in this work bring SiMOS spin qubits at temperatures above 1 K into the realm of fault tolerance."
  ],
